Go live your life. Create new experiences. Be with people you love. Then come back and make art. 

I need to remind myself that stepping away from the canvas and absorbing the world around me is fuel. It’s an essential part of my art journey.

Moments of introspection are becoming a big part of my painting process. Every mark made has the potential to influence the next and cascades with my thoughts and feelings along the way. I don’t necessarily know what the end result is going to be. There isn’t a master plan. I can guide it but I don’t fully control it and that to me is exciting. #art #painting #artwork #artistsoninstagram #portrait #introspection

I’ve been taking a little bit of a different approach to my portraits lately and the results have been so much better. I start with a 2H pencil that is sharpened to long point with a knife. This allows me to use more of the pencil on its side. Also, holding the pencil this way feels more natural and marks feel more organic. #art #sketchbook #pencil #portrait #artvsartist

I’m opening up my commissions for the first time ever! 

In efforts to make a transition into new areas of art and follow the path to drawing things I love and care about I have opened some spots for commissions. These are traditional pencil portraits on toned grey paper. I will draw you, your friends, your loved ones, your dog! This is also great for gifts to those you care about. 

Traditional portraiture is my passion and I want share my craft with other lovers of art. 

If this is something your are interested in, DM me for more info.

Exploring unconventional painting surfaces. 
Oil on primed corrugated cardboard.

3, 2, 1, Let’s jam! I’m working with new unconventional surfaces. Painting some eyes, ears and noses on torn up cardboard. I’ve seen paintings on surfaces like this before and the idea of doing the torn edges came to me when I was exploring the art institute. I was admiring some of their restored sculptures and noticing the missing facial features that had broken off over time. It clearly had pieces missing but still felt complete.
